{"slug": "how-to-create-a-temporary-email", "title": "How to Create a Temporary Email Address (Step-by-Step Guide)", "h1": "How to Create a Temporary Email", "desc": "A step-by-step guide to creating a free temporary email address in seconds - no sign-up - and using it to receive verification emails and OTP codes safely.", "bodyHtml": "<p>If you want to sign up for something without handing over your real inbox, the fastest path is to create a temporary email. A temporary email address is a free, disposable inbox you can use right away &mdash; no sign-up, no password, nothing to remember later. You make a temp mail in seconds, point it at whatever site is asking for an email, read the confirmation or verification code that arrives, and walk away. This guide shows you exactly how to create a temporary email address with Temp Mail, step by step, plus practical tips for getting the most out of it.</p>\n\n<h2>What a temporary email actually does</h2>\n<p>Temp Mail gives you a working inbox instantly. It is receive-only, which means messages come <em>in</em> but you do not send anything out. That is fine for the most common job people need an email for: confirming a download, finishing a registration, or catching a one-time code. Inboxes are cleared periodically, so nothing piles up and nothing sticks around forever. It is free and unlimited, so you can spin up as many addresses as you need. The catch worth stating up front: this is not for banking, work accounts, or anything important you would be upset to lose access to.</p>\n\n<h2>How to create a temporary email: step by step</h2>\n<p>The whole process takes under a minute. Here is the order to follow.</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Open the generator.</strong> Go to the <a href='/temp-mail-generator'>Temp Mail generator</a>. An address is created for you automatically the moment the page loads, so you may already have one waiting before you do anything else.</li>\n<li><strong>Customize the name and domain (or take the random one).</strong> If you would rather pick your own, type a custom name in front of the @ and choose from one of the available domains. Want something forgettable instead? Leave the random address as is. Either works.</li>\n<li><strong>Copy the address.</strong> Click the copy button next to your inbox name. Now it is on your clipboard and ready to paste anywhere.</li>\n<li><strong>Use it on any site.</strong> Go back to the site or app asking for an email, paste your temp address into its sign-up or download field, and submit the form.</li>\n<li><strong>Read the incoming mail or code.</strong> Switch back to your Temp Mail tab. New messages show up in real time &mdash; refresh if you are impatient. Open the message, grab the link or the verification code, and you are done.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>That is the entire flow. No account, no inbox cleanup, no password reset emails six months from now.</p>\n\n<h2>Tips for using temp mail well</h2>\n<p>A few small habits make this smoother:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Keep the Temp Mail tab open while you finish the sign-up on the other site. Codes can arrive within seconds, and you do not want to be hunting for the tab.</li>\n<li>Copy the address rather than retyping it. A single wrong character means the message lands in an inbox you cannot see.</li>\n<li>Use a custom name when you want something you will recognize later, and a random one when you just need an address and do not care what it says.</li>\n<li>Finish what you came to do before the inbox is cleared. Since inboxes are cleared periodically, treat each address as short-lived.</li>\n<li>If you want to compare it with a fixed-lifetime option, the <a href='/10-minute-mail'>10 minute mail</a> page explains a slightly different approach to the same idea.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Creating multiple or fresh addresses</h2>\n<p>Because the service is free and unlimited, you are not stuck with one inbox. Need a clean address for a different site? Generate a new one and the old messages stop mattering. This is handy when you want to keep two sign-ups separate, or when an address has been used once and you would rather start fresh. Open the generator, make a new address, copy it, and carry on. There is no limit and no cost, so reach for a fresh address whenever it is convenient. If you want the broader picture on how these throwaway inboxes work, the <a href='/disposable-email'>disposable email</a> overview covers it.</p>\n\n<h2>What to do if a site blocks your address</h2>\n<p>Some sites try to reject disposable addresses. If a form refuses your temp mail, do not give up on the first try:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Generate a new address on a <em>different</em> domain. Temp Mail offers multiple domains, and a site that blocks one may accept another.</li>\n<li>Try a custom name instead of the random string &mdash; some filters flag long random-looking handles.</li>\n<li>Refresh the generator to get an entirely new address and attempt the sign-up again.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If a site flatly will not accept any temporary address, that is usually a sign it expects a long-term relationship with you. For accounts like that, use your real email instead.</p>\n\n<h2>How to receive an OTP or verification code</h2>\n<p>One-time passcodes are one of the most common reasons people make a temp mail. The good news is that OTP and verification codes arrive in real time, so the process is quick:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Paste your temp address into the site that needs to verify you.</li>\n<li>Request the code and submit the form.</li>\n<li>Switch to your Temp Mail inbox and watch for the new message to land.</li>\n<li>Open it, copy the code, and paste it back into the site before it expires.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Codes often expire in a few minutes, so move quickly. For a deeper walkthrough, see our guide on using <a href='/blog/temp-mail-for-otp-verification-codes'>temp mail for OTP and verification codes</a>.</p>\n\n<h2>Common mistakes to avoid</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Closing the tab too soon.</strong> If you leave before the message arrives, you may lose the address and have to start over.</li>\n<li><strong>Mistyping the address.</strong> Always copy and paste. Hand-typing invites errors you cannot recover from.</li>\n<li><strong>Trying to reply.</strong> Temp Mail is receive-only. If a site needs a real back-and-forth conversation, this is the wrong tool.</li>\n<li><strong>Using it for something important.</strong> Inboxes are cleared periodically and there is no password recovery, so do not attach it to anything you cannot afford to lose.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>When NOT to use a temporary email</h2>\n<p>Temp Mail is great for low-stakes sign-ups, downloads, trials, and quick verifications. It is the wrong choice when the account matters. Skip it for banking and financial services, your job or work systems, government portals, healthcare logins, and any account you intend to keep and recover later. Those need a permanent inbox you control. If you are weighing the trade-offs, our article on <a href='/blog/is-temp-mail-safe'>whether temp mail is safe</a> goes into more detail about where the line sits.</p>\n\n<h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>\n<h3>Do I need to sign up or create a password?</h3>\n<p>No. There is no sign-up and no password. The address is generated for you and works immediately.</p>\n\n<h3>Can I choose my own email name?</h3>\n<p>Yes. You can type a custom name and choose from multiple domains, or just take the random address the generator creates for you.</p>\n\n<h3>How long does the inbox last?</h3>\n<p>Inboxes are cleared periodically, so treat each address as temporary. Read what you need right away rather than counting on it later.</p>\n\n<h3>Can I send email from a temp address?</h3>\n<p>No. Temp Mail is receive-only. It is built to catch incoming messages and codes, not to send mail out.</p>\n\n<p>Creating a temporary email address really is this simple: open the generator, pick or accept a name, copy, and use it. For low-stakes sign-ups and quick codes, it saves your real inbox from clutter and spam. Ready to make a temp mail of your own? Head to the <a href='/'>Temp Mail home page</a> and get an address in seconds.</p>"}
